ltshire, England":"Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England","Of Burbach,Wiltshire,England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Burbage, Wiltshire, England":"Burbage, Wiltshire, England","Easton Priory, Easton, Wiltshire, England":"Easton Town, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sturmy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Sturmey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sturmey","meanings":["English: (i) nickname from Middle English  <i>stormi</i> ‘stormy’ (Old French  <i>estormi</i>), for someone with a stormy temperament.  Compare  Storm   relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Sturmi</i>,  <i>Sturmy</i> (Old French * <i>Estourmi</i>, Continental Germanic  <i>Sturmi</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":38,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":47,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Henry de Sturmy was born about 1290, in Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England as the son of Henry Esturmy and Margaret Hussey. He had at least 3 sons with Margery de l'Orti. He died in 1338, at the age of 49, and was buried in Easton Town, Wiltshire, England."},"et":{"about 1290–1338":"umbes 1290–1338","1290–1338":"1290–1338","1292–1341":"1292–1341","1311–1382":"1311–1382","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1325–1381":"1325–1381","–1305":"–1305","1265–1320":"1265–1320","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1341":"1341","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1311